Maharshi Vasishtha's teaching to =
Lord Rama is clear in Yoga Vaasishtham. The goal of existence and sadhana i=
s self-realization. Siddhis are to be neither specifically sought nor speci=
fically avoided, by a seeker of Self. If Nature gives one some siddhi(s), o=
ne should accept them with neither excitement nor disappointment. But one s=
hould NOT run after them, for they are neither necessary nor sufficient for=
 self-realization and liberation. 
=C2=A0 
Vivekananda used the same princi=
ple when Ramakirishna proposed to give his siddhis to Vivekananda. He asked=
 whether the siddhis will enable him to realize god. Ramakrishna said no. V=
ivekananda firmly declined the offer then! Of course, when Ramakrishna gave=
 them anyway later, he accepted them. Vivekananda's two actions demonstrate=
 Vasishtha's instructions well. 
=C2=A0 
*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=
=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 * 
=C2=A0 
Let us use=
 the analogy of climbing a hill. Climbing hill is one's spiritual sadhana. =
Reaching the top is liberation. Different people climb the hill from differ=
ent sides and using different paths. There may be trees with nice fruits on=
 the sides of the road. They are siddhis or special abilities. 
=C2=A0 
If =
one gets distracted, starts climbing the trees and collecting fruits, one's=
 journey gets delayed and one may not reach the top. That is why Vasishtha =
says a seeker of Self does not pursue any siddhis. 
=C2=A0 
But if some fru=
its fall in one's lap by themselves, one can keep them. Similarly, siddhis =
that come to one by themselves can be accepted by a seeker of Self. 
=C2=A0=
 
Now an important distinction: 
=C2=A0 
There are some trees that are foun=
d at lower altitudes also, but some really special trees are found at very =
high altitudes only. If one has such a fruit, it shows that one has climbed=
 great heights. Similarly, some siddhis do not mean much, but some siddhis =
are very special and only really elevated sadhakas can obtain them (whether=
 by trying or without trying). If a sadhakas demonstrates such a siddhi, yo=
u can see that one progressed a lot. However, the key is that one who climb=
ed the same or more distance may not have that or any other fruit. 
=C2=A0 =

*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=
=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 * 
=C2=A0 
Unlike in the example of climbing hill, which is=
 an external activity, spiritual progress in real life is *internal*. There=
 is NO way for anyone to know for sure how much progress one has made, how =
much self-control one has internally and what exactly goes on in one's mind=
. We may try to judge it from external factors such as actions, words etc, =
but it is not necessarily accurate. 
=C2=A0 
Here, some people swayed by si=
ddhis may be tempted to use one's siddhis to judge how high one climbed. Bu=
t that is faulty. One person who reached the absolute top may not have any =
fruits, while one person who still has ways to climb may have gotten some r=
eally nice fruit. Using externaslly demonstrable siddhis that are neither n=
ecessary nor sufficient for Self-realization as a measure of one's progress=
 is unsound. 
=C2=A0 
Given that spiritual progress is internal, how can we=
 judge it and compare people then? Well, we need not and should not. Only a=
 sarvaantaryaami - a perfected being who has access to each being's interna=
l state - can do that. 
=C2=A0 
*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=
 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 * 
